Files:
- plugins/spotify/src/spotify-api.ts (export a resetInterceptor() function for use by teardown)
- plugins/spotify/src/index.ts (add teardown() method to SpotifyPlugin class)

Context:
spotify-api.ts (lines 21-53):
  let interceptorInstalled = false;
  const installInterceptor = (): void => {
    if (typeof window === 'undefined') return;
    const origFetch = (globalThis as Record<string, unknown>).__spotifyOrigFetch as typeof fetch | undefined;
    if (origFetch && interceptorInstalled) return;  // guard against re-patching
    const realFetch = origFetch ?? window.fetch;
    (globalThis as Record<string, unknown>).__spotifyOrigFetch = realFetch;
    window.fetch = function (...args) {
      // intercept Bearer tokens
      return realFetch.apply(this, args);
    };
    interceptorInstalled = true;
  };
  installInterceptor(); // called at module load

The guard at line 27 prevents double-patching on re-injection (checks origFetch AND interceptorInstalled). But there is no teardown path.

Fix:
1. In spotify-api.ts, export a new function `resetInterceptor()` that:
   - Restores window.fetch from globalThis.__spotifyOrigFetch
   - Deletes globalThis.__spotifyOrigFetch
   - Sets interceptorInstalled = false
2. In index.ts, implement teardown() that calls resetInterceptor()

Constraints:
- Do NOT change the auth token capture logic
- resetInterceptor() must handle the case where __spotifyOrigFetch is not set (no-op)
- The interceptorInstalled flag must be set back to false so that a fresh IIFE injection (re-injection after teardown) correctly calls installInterceptor() again
